SIMPLE: insolence
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insolence
<hw>In"so*lence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>insolence</ets>, L. <ets>insolentia</ets>. See
<er>Insolent</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being unusual or novel.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quality of being insolent; pride or haughtiness
manifested in contemptuous and overbearing treatment of others; arrogant
contempt; brutal impudence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flown with <qex>insolence</qex> and wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Insolent conduct or treatment; insult.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Loaded with fetters and <qex>insolences</qex> from the
soldiers.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insolence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Insolence
<hw>In"so*lence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To insult.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Eikon Basilike.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insolency</ent>⟦br⟧
